Case Study 1

Hieu Nguyen

2022-10-27

Author: Hieu Nguyen

Date: 27 Oct 2022

Intro

This is a case study I completed about a fictional company, Cyclistic. As a junior data analyst on their team, I will follow the data analysis process; ask, prepare, process, analyze, share, and act.

About the company

In 2016, Cyclistic launched a successful bike-share offering. Since then, the program has grown to a fleet of 5,824 bicycles that are geotracked and locked into a network of 692 stations across Chicago. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system anytime. Until now, Cyclistics marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members. Cyclistics finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Although the pricing flexibility helps Cyclistic attract more customers, Moreno believes that maximizing the number of annual members will be key to future growth. Rather than creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers, Moreno believes there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs. Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

Ask

Businesss task: How do annual members and casual riders use Cyclistic bikes differently?

Prepare

Data Source

The data is stored in the public dataset tripdata-cyclists from the website https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html and the last 12 months of data was concidered. The data has been made available by Motivate International Inc.under this license: https://ride.divvybikes.com/data-license-agreement. The data is organized in 13 columns in 12 differnt CSV files, one for each month.

Preparation of data for analysis

Data cleaning in spreadsheets will be time-consuming and slow compared to SQL or R. Because the combined size of all the 12 datasets is larger than 1Gb. I decided to use R. Because I can do wrangling and analysis/ visualizations in the same platform.

Perhaps it is because members use bikeshare services as a means of transportation to get to work, whereas casual do not. Act

Key takeaways

In terms of the number of trips, Member rider is more on weekdays, and Casual rider is more on weekends. During the daytime, Member makes more trips than Casual rider, except for the hours from 10 pm to 4 am.

In terms of average time duration, Casual rider is twice as long as Member rider. In the monthly surveys, the average duration of the member rider is less volatile, while that of the casual rider is much more variable in months compared.

In terms of the type of bike used, Member rider uses mostly classic bikes. Casual rider uses mostly electric bikes, Member rider does not use dock bikes, which is also the least used of the three models.

Recommendations

Considering all of the data, I have three recomendations for converting casual riders into member riders:

Discount for weekdays, let Casual rider use the bikeshare service more during the weekday. Discount for the second and third time using the bicycle of the day, let Casual rider use the bikeshare more during the day.

Extra charges will apply if travel time exceeds 20 minutes. It will interfere with Casual rider when they have a long duration of travel, so they will consider moving to Member rider.

Discount if clients use classic bicycle.
